(Description:)221 396 MS
(Three problems, all of which are somewhat related.)521 441 MS
(\(1\) )521 531 MS
(mem_fun_t's operator\(\)\(\) is not a const member function.  This means that you can't pass a )576 531 MS
(mem_fun_t)1965 531 MS
(to any function that takes its argument by const reference.  \(Which many of the STL algorithms do.\))521 576 MS
(This is a fairly trivial problem, but, from experience, it's one that users will have a lot of trouble with.  The)521 666 MS
(sorts of error messages that you get when you pass a function object by const reference, and it doesn't have a)521 711 MS
(const operator\(\)\(\), are very hard to understand.  People will spend hours looking at their code and trying to)521 756 MS
(figure out what's wrong.)521 801 MS
(\(2\) You can't apply a )521 891 MS
(mem_fun_t<S, T> to an object of type const )848 891 MS
(T*, but only to one of type )1528 891 MS
(T*.  This is a)1941 891 MS
(serious limitation: it means that the )521 936 MS
(mem_fun_t )1071 936 MS
(adaptor can't be used)1255 936 MS
(\(3\) You can't create a )521 1026 MS
(mem_fun_t where the member function pointer is initialized to a const member)856 1026 MS
(function.  If, for example, you have)521 1071 MS
(   )521 1161 MS
(struct A {)551 1161 MS
(     )521 1206 MS
(int x;)571 1206 MS
(     )521 1251 MS
(int twice\(\) const { return 2*x; })571 1251 MS
(   };)521 1296 MS
(then )521 1386 MS
(mem_fun\()597 1386 MS
(A::twice\) doesn't work, because the argument is of type ")754 1386 MS
(int \(A::*\)\(\) const"  and )1619 1386 MS
(mem_fun)1974 1386 MS
(expects its argument to be of type "S \(T::*\)\(\)".)521 1431 MS
(Proposed Resolution:)221 1476 MS
(Change 20.3.8 [)521 1521 MS
(lib.member.pointer.adaptors] to make operator\(\) const in )764 1521 MS
(mem_fun_t, mem_fun1_t,)1640 1521 MS
(mem_fun_ref_t, and mem_fun1_ref_t.)521 1566 MS
